Artificial Intelligence (AI)

1. Definition
AI is the field of computer science that enables machines to mimic human intelligence.

2. History
AI officially began in 1956 at the Dartmouth Conference.

3. Goals
Create systems that can learn, reason, solve problems and make decisions.

4. Characteristics
Learning, reasoning, perception, planning and decision making.

5. Advantages
Automation, accuracy, speed and scalability.

6. Disadvantages
Bias, privacy concerns, job displacement and high cost.

7. Applications
Chatbots, healthcare, finance, robotics, self-driving cars and recommendation systems.

8. Types of AI

8.1 Based on Capabilities

8.1.1 Narrow AI (ANI)
AI specialized for a single task.

8.1.2 General AI (AGI)
AI capable of performing any intellectual task a human can do.

8.1.3 Super AI (ASI)
AI that surpasses human intelligence in all domains.

8.2 Based on Functionality

8.2.1 Reactive Machines
AI that reacts only to current input without memory.

8.2.2 Limited Memory
AI that learns using historical data.

8.2.3 Theory of Mind
AI capable of understanding emotions and intentions.

8.2.4 Self-Aware AI
AI possessing consciousness and self-awareness.

9. AI Life Cycle
Problem → Data → Training → Evaluation → Deployment → Monitoring.

10. AI vs ML vs DL

AI
Broad field of creating intelligent machines.

ML
Subset of AI that learns from data.

DL
Subset of ML using deep neural networks.

11. Mathematics for AI

11.1 Linear Algebra
Used for vectors, matrices and neural networks.

11.2 Calculus
Used for optimization and gradient descent.

11.3 Probability
Used for uncertainty and prediction.

11.4 Statistics
Used for data analysis and model evaluation.

11.5 Optimization
Used to minimize loss functions.

12. Machine Learning
Enables systems to learn patterns from data.

12.1 Supervised Learning
Learns using labeled data.

12.2 Unsupervised Learning
Finds hidden patterns in unlabeled data.

12.3 Reinforcement Learning
Learns through rewards and penalties.

13. Deep Learning
Uses multi-layer neural networks to learn complex patterns.

14. Neural Networks
Computational models inspired by the human brain.

15. Computer Vision
Enables machines to understand images and videos.

16. Natural Language Processing (NLP)
Enables machines to understand and generate human language.

17. Generative AI
Creates new content such as text, images, audio and video.

18. Large Language Models (LLMs)
AI models trained on massive text datasets for language tasks.

19. Prompt Engineering
Designing effective prompts to improve AI responses.

20. RAG
Combines retrieval systems with LLMs for accurate answers.

21. Fine Tuning
Adapting a pre-trained model to a specific task.

22. AI Agents
Autonomous systems that plan, reason and take actions.

23. MLOps
Practices for deploying and maintaining ML systems.

24. AI Frameworks

24.1 TensorFlow
Google's deep learning framework.

24.2 PyTorch
Popular deep learning framework by Meta.

24.3 Scikit-Learn
Machine learning library for classical algorithms.

24.4 Keras
High-level API for deep learning.

24.5 Hugging Face
Platform for transformers and LLMs.

25. AI Ethics
Ensures fairness, transparency and responsible AI usage.

26. Responsible AI
Building AI systems that are safe, ethical and trustworthy.

27. Explainable AI (XAI)
Makes AI decisions understandable to humans.

28. AI Security
Protecting AI systems from attacks and misuse.

29. AI Projects

29.1 Chatbot
Conversational AI assistant.

29.2 Recommendation System
Suggests products, movies or content.

29.3 Face Recognition
Identifies individuals from images.

29.4 Spam Detection
Classifies emails as spam or not spam.

29.5 AI Voice Assistant
Responds to voice commands.

30. AI Interview Preparation
Focus on AI fundamentals, ML, DL, NLP, CV, GenAI and projects.

